13 WHEREAS, secondhand smoke exposure contributes to approximately 41,000 deaths among
14 nonsmoking adults and 400 deaths in infants each year. Secondhand smoke causes stroke,
15 lung cancer, coronary heart disease, and reproductive health complications in adults.
16 Children who are exposed to secondhand smoke are at increased risk for sudden infant death
17 syndrome (SIDS), acute respiratory infections, middle ear disease, more severe asthma,
18 respiratory symptoms, and slowed lung growth; and
19 WHEREAS, smoking related illness in the United States costs more than $300 billion each
20 year, including more than $225 billion for direct medical care for adults and more than $156
21 billion in lost productivity, including $5.6 billion in lost productivity due to secondhand
22 smoke exposure; and
23 WHEREAS, it would be beneficial to examine the cost of smoking, including short-term and
24 long-term health care costs, the impact on Medicaid and Medicare, childhood health costs
25 resulting from secondhand smoke exposure, and the loss of worker productivity attributed
26 to smoking.
27 NOW, THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES:
28 (1) Creation of House study committee. There is created the House Study Committee
29 on the Costs and Effects of Smoking.
30 (2) Members and officers.
31 (A) The committee shall be composed of five members of the House of
32 Representatives.
33 (B) The Speaker of the House of Representatives shall appoint all members of the
34 committee and shall designate one of such members as chairperson.
